article.description:
Janel McCarville tied her career-high with 23
points, and Lindsay Whalen added 21 and a career-high 12 rebounds
to lead No. 9 Minnesota over Illinois 77-62 Thursday night.
article.headline: McCarville has career-high 23 points in victory
article.linkText: McCarville, Whalen combine to lead Gophers over Illinois
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Although Minnesota's opponents are always
geared up for point guard Lindsay Whalen, the Golden Gophers showed
their inside game is just as tough to defend.

	   Janel McCarville tied her career high with 23 points, and Whalen
added 21 and a career-high 12 rebounds to lead (No. 11 ESPN/USA Today, No. 9 AP) Minnesota over
Illinois 77-62 Thursday night.

	   McCarville scored 15 of her points in the second half for the
Golden Gophers (13-1, 2-1 Big Ten), who regrouped after losing
their first game of the season on Monday -- a 83-53 defeat to Penn
State -- to snap the Illini's four-game winning streak.

	   "I felt like I played hard (against Penn State) but I didn't
feel I did everything I could have,'' said McCarville, who finished
with 10 points on Monday. "Tonight, I just came out with the
energy that this is going to be my game and I'm going to show
everybody that I can play.''

	   With Illinois' loss, the 17th-ranked Nittany Lions, who defeated
Iowa 86-52 on Thursday, moved into sole possession of first place
in the Big Ten.

	   Cindy Dallas led the Illini (10-3, 2-1) with 17 points. Angelina
Williams added 13 and Jere Issenmann had 12 points on 4-of-10
shooting from 3-point range.

	   Illinois led through most of the game thanks to strong inside
play on both ends of the court. The Illini held Minnesota to 38.5-percent shooting in the first half.

	   "They took us out of what we wanted to do in the first five
minutes of the game,'' Minnesota coach Pam Borton said. "We just
weren't attacking the basket.''

	   That changed in the second half as the Gophers abandoned their
long-range jumpshot and went inside. McCarville got open underneath
several times for easy layups while Whalen and Corrin Von Wald were
too quick for Illinois' backcourt.

	   "We wanted to get the ball inside,'' Borton said. "You score
inside and it takes the pressure off the guards and now they've got
to double down and the outside opens up.''

	   The Gophers went 16-for-23 from the foul line -- Whalen went
11-for-12. Whalen finished with eight assists. Von Wald had 14
points for Minnesota.

	   Trailing 46-40, the Gophers ripped off a 13-0 run to take
control of the game. Whalen's free throws with 12:56 left pulled
Minnesota to 46-45. The Gophers then forced two straight Illinois
turnovers, and McCarville hit two more foul shots to give Minnesota
its first lead.

	   Shannon Schonrock added a 3-pointer and McCarville another free
throw to extend Minnesota's lead to 51-46 with 11:01 to play.

	   "Call it mental, call it defensive, it was a definite
breakdown,'' Illinois coach Theresa Grentz said. "When you have
those, you have to give credit to the other team because they
caused that.''

	   Minnesota finished 11 steals, four by Von Wald.

	   "We weren't making the passes we needed to make,'' Grentz said.
"There were uncontested turnovers, throwing the ball across the
floor, we didn't finish inside.''

	   The Gophers shot 19-for-32 from the floor in the second half.

	   The Illini took an 8-0 lead and never trailed in the first half.
Illinois went 6-for-12 from 3-point range in the opening period
while the Gophers struggled.

	   "It was just shots that we normally put down,'' Whalen said.
"They got off to that quick 8-0 lead and we just decided we had to
buckle down on defense.''

	   Williams' 3 gave the Illini a 23-14 lead. Dallas made it 25-16
with a layup with 4:52 left in the half.

	   Whalen and McCarville fueled an 8-0 run to pull Minnesota to
25-24 with 1:38 left to bring the crowd to its feet.

	   But Aminata Yanni hit a 3 and a pull-up jumper to give Illinois
a 30-26 halftime lead.
